### Swift Initializers

Initializers prepare instances of a type for use. They ensure all stored properties have initial values before the instance is ready. Swift provides multiple initializer options.

**Designated Initializers:**

Designated initializers are the primary initializers for a class. They must ensure all properties have values and must call a designated superclass initializer.

```swift
class Person {
    var name: String
    var age: Int

    // Designated initializer
    init(name: String, age: Int) {
        self.name = name
        self.age = age
    }
}

let person = Person(name: "Alice", age: 30)
```

**Initialization Rules:**

| Rule | Description |
|------|-------------|
| All stored properties | Must have initial values before init completes |
| Optional properties | Automatically initialized to nil |
| Constant properties | Can be set during initialization |
| Superclass init | Must be called after local properties are set |

```swift
// Optional properties default to nil
class User {
    let id: Int
    var name: String
    var email: String?

    init(id: Int, name: String, email: String? = nil) {
        self.id = id      // Set 'let' property here
        self.name = name
        self.email = email  // Optional, can set or leave nil
    }
}
```

**Required Initializers:**

```swift
class SomeClass {
    required init() {
        // Every subclass must implement this
    }
}

class Subclass: SomeClass {
    required init() {
        // Must provide implementation
    }
}
```

**Initializer Delegation (Value Types):**

```swift
struct Size {
    var width: Double
    var height: Double

    init(width: Double, height: Double) {
        self.width = width
        self.height = height
    }

    // Delegating initializer
    init(side: Double) {
        self.init(width: side, height: side)
    }
}
```

> **Key Point:** Classes have designated and convenience initializers. Structs get a memberwise initializer automatically unless you define custom initializers.

All properties must be initialized. Optionals get `nil` automatically. Constants can be assigned only during initialization.

codeExample:
import Foundation

class Product {
    let name: String
    var price: Double
    var category: String?
    var inStock: Bool

    // Designated initializer
    init(name: String, price: Double, category: String? = nil, inStock: Bool = true) {
        self.name = name
        self.price = price
        self.category = category
        self.inStock = inStock
    }

    // Convenience initializer for on-sale items
    convenience init(name: String, originalPrice: Double, discountPercent: Double) {
        let discountedPrice = originalPrice * (1 - discountPercent / 100)
        self.init(name: name, price: discountedPrice)
    }
}

let laptop = Product(name: "MacBook Pro", price: 2499.00, category: "Electronics")
let saleItem = Product(name: "Headphones", originalPrice: 199.99, discountPercent: 20)

print("\(laptop.name): $\(laptop.price) (\(laptop.category ?? "General"))")
print("\(saleItem.name): $\(String(format: "%.2f", saleItem.price)) (on sale!)")
